00:14:03.410 --> 00:14:07.090
about him, and also
by people who don't.

00:14:07.090 --> 00:14:14.730
And he is at a point in his life
where he is either going to have

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:18.310
to discover that he's not as big
a fool as everybody claims he is,

00:14:18.310 --> 00:14:21.970
and that he thinks he
is, or his life is over.

00:14:21.970 --> 00:14:24.680
Everything is at stake for him.

00:14:24.680 --> 00:14:28.710
And what I discovered
was the longer I spent --

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:32.180
and this happens to me a lot --

00:14:32.180 --> 00:14:38.350
but the longer I spend inside
somebody's thoughts and fears

00:14:38.350 --> 00:14:44.350
and aspirations, the
more I come to care.

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:47.220
And what I have to hope when I'm
foolish enough to do something

00:14:47.220 --> 00:14:51.330
like this, to ask you care about
somebody when you have reasons,

00:14:51.330 --> 00:14:56.480
good and sufficient reasons not
to, what I have to do is believe

00:14:56.480 --> 00:15:00.600
that I can convince you that this
person is worth spending time with,

00:15:00.600 --> 00:15:04.280
and maybe investing some
emotional attachment to.

00:15:04.280 --> 00:15:06.110
&gt;&gt; I got really emotionally
attached to Doug Raymer.

00:15:06.110 --> 00:15:07.410
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:15:07.410 --> 00:15:08.710
&gt;&gt; I'll say.

00:15:08.710 --> 00:15:10.010
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:15:10.010 --> 00:15:11.310
So did I.

00:15:11.310 --> 00:15:12.610
&gt;&gt; What made you want
to go back to Sully?

00:15:12.610 --> 00:15:14.370
What is it you wanted to explore
about Sully again as a character?

00:15:14.370 --> 00:15:16.880
This is, again, for those of
you who haven't read the book,

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:18.630
but maybe thinking about it.

00:15:18.630 --> 00:15:22.900
This is just -- I was thinking,
is irascible the right word?

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:25.300
I'm not sure that's the
right word, but I love using

00:15:25.300 --> 00:15:26.600
that word, so it gives me --

00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:27.900
&gt;&gt; Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:15:27.900 --> 00:15:29.200
Yeah.

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:30.500
&gt;&gt; The opportunity to do so.

00:15:30.500 --> 00:15:31.800
But, you know, he's
just a, you know,

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:33.420
he's a guy that's just
kind of a laborer, really.

00:15:33.420 --> 00:15:36.230
A construction worker, and
does all the dirty jobs,

00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:39.890
and drinks a lot and, you
know, lets people down, and --

00:15:39.890 --> 00:15:42.030
but he's a smart guy
and you get to really

00:15:42.030 --> 00:15:45.020
like him in both of these books.

00:15:45.020 --> 00:15:46.320
Why did you want to go back?

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:47.620
What did you want to
discover about --

00:15:47.620 --> 00:15:49.500
and what's changed
about him, do you think?

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:51.250
Besides the fact that
he kind of, now,

00:15:51.250 --> 00:15:54.310
gets along with Doug
Raymer, actually?

00:15:54.310 --> 00:16:00.410
&gt;&gt; Well, yeah, yeah, well, one of
the obvious reasons for going back

00:16:00.410 --> 00:16:06.290
and writing this book and
resurrecting Sully is that Sully,

00:16:06.290 --> 00:16:10.330
like one or two other of my rogue
male characters that you can kind

00:16:10.330 --> 00:16:13.320
of trace through Dallas
Younger in the first book,

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:16.930
and Sam Hall in the second,
and then Sully in the third,

00:16:16.930 --> 00:16:20.410
all the way through Max Roby,
you know, in Miles' father

00:16:20.410 --> 00:16:23.700
in "Empire Falls," and now
revisiting Sully again.

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:30.060
One of the principle advantages,
one of the principle reasons

00:16:30.060 --> 00:16:37.410
to do something like that is that
all of those characters were based,

00:16:37.410 --> 00:16:42.590
to a large extent, on my own
father, who, in real life,

00:16:42.590 --> 00:16:46.140 position:56%
I just never got enough of in a way.

00:16:46.140 --> 00:16:49.790
He and my mom split up when I
was young, and so I spent most

00:16:49.790 --> 00:16:54.710
of my youth kind of in longing
for a man who wasn't around.

00:16:54.710 --> 00:16:59.350
And he became more interested
in me around the age of 18,

00:16:59.350 --> 00:17:03.600
because back then in New
York, you could drink at 18.

00:17:03.600 --> 00:17:04.900
&gt;&gt; That's right.

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:06.200
I grew up in New York, too.

00:17:06.200 --> 00:17:11.660 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yeah. So I became interested -- I
became more interesting to my father

00:17:11.660 --> 00:17:12.960
when I was old enough to drink.

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:17.070
And so during my college
years when I came back

00:17:17.070 --> 00:17:20.440
and was working road construction
with him, I really got to know him

00:17:20.440 --> 00:17:23.570
and got to know what made him tick.

00:17:23.570 --> 00:17:26.530
And we became good friends.

00:17:26.530 --> 00:17:34.080
In a way, it wasn't, I mean
there was a father-son aspect

00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:39.380
to our relationship,
but it was a little --

00:17:39.380 --> 00:17:40.680
it was more complex than that,

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:44.510
because we hadn't been
father and son for so long.

00:17:44.510 --> 00:17:48.970
And because I -- and it wasn't that
long after that that he became ill.

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:56.240
And so I just kind of never
got my fill of the man.

00:17:56.240 --> 00:18:03.760
And so returning to North Bath
and resurrecting Sully was

00:18:03.760 --> 00:18:07.670
at one level kind of Psych 101
level, was just a way for me

00:18:07.670 --> 00:18:10.260
to spend more time with my father.

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:12.660
The other interesting
thing, though, about this,

00:18:12.660 --> 00:18:19.150
was that because the wonderful
Robert Benton movie was made,

00:18:19.150 --> 00:18:29.090
of that novel, I was not only able
to resurrect Sully, my character,

00:18:29.090 --> 00:18:32.500
and my father, the real person
whom this book was based on.

00:18:32.500 --> 00:18:33.800
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:37.070
&gt;&gt; I also got to resurrect
Paul Newman, who --

00:18:37.070 --> 00:18:39.740
Paul, I worked with Paul
on three different movies.

00:18:39.740 --> 00:18:43.420 position:56%
He was -- I wouldn't say we had like
an intimate friendship or anything

00:18:43.420 --> 00:18:45.950
like that, but we both --

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:50.830
We saw the world in the same way.

00:18:50.830 --> 00:18:57.700
And he was -- he really
liked writers a lot.

00:18:57.700 --> 00:19:04.000
And I discovered in
resurrecting Sully that because

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.450
of his incredible portrayal
of my character,

00:19:07.450 --> 00:19:12.640
I no longer had sole
proprietorship over Sully anymore.

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:16.240
Because, you know, in
every scene that I wrote --

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:19.670
when I was writing "Nobody's Fool,"

00:19:19.670 --> 00:19:23.550
in every scene I was
seeing my father.

00:19:23.550 --> 00:19:25.930
Now I'm seeing -- it
goes back and forth

00:19:25.930 --> 00:19:30.440
between seeing my father
and seeing Paul Newman.

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:33.570
Who, by the way, looked
nothing like my father.

00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:37.720 position:56%
You can imagine my mother's surprise

00:19:37.720 --> 00:19:40.700
when Paul Newman was
cast to play her husband.

00:19:40.700 --> 00:19:45.650
I mean, it's just --
the mind boggles.

00:19:45.650 --> 00:19:50.230
So there was this -- and, you
know, the entire book was about --

00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:52.930
the whole book takes
place over Memorial Day,

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:55.240
and it's a book about memory.

00:19:55.240 --> 00:19:56.540
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:19:56.540 --> 00:20:00.810
&gt;&gt; And so until I began writing it,
I didn't realize what the upside

00:20:00.810 --> 00:20:03.110
to this book was going to be.

00:20:03.110 --> 00:20:11.680
And that it was going to plumb
depths in me and needs in me

00:20:11.680 --> 00:20:14.770
that I just didn't suspect until
I actually began writing it.

00:20:14.770 --> 00:20:16.070
&gt;&gt; So this raises another question.

00:20:16.070 --> 00:20:18.240
I was wondering about this,
exactly what you just brought up,

00:20:18.240 --> 00:20:21.880
because I had a hard time getting
Paul Newman out of my head.

00:20:21.880 --> 00:20:23.690
And I don't know that that's

00:20:23.690 --> 00:20:26.960
who I would've imagined had he
not been there to begin with.

00:20:26.960 --> 00:20:28.260
&gt;&gt; Yeah, yeah.

00:20:28.260 --> 00:20:29.710
&gt;&gt; Because I think I
saw the movie first.

00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:34.120
But Philip Seymour
Hoffman played Doug Raybey.

00:20:34.120 --> 00:20:35.740
&gt;&gt; Doug Raymer, yeah.

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:37.040
&gt;&gt; Doug Raymer, I'm sorry.

00:20:37.040 --> 00:20:38.340
&gt;&gt; Yeah, yeah.

00:20:38.340 --> 00:20:42.000
&gt;&gt; And so is he now in your head?

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:43.300
&gt;&gt; Oh, God, yes.

00:20:43.300 --> 00:20:45.420
&gt;&gt; And as you were writing the
book, were you actually seeing him?

00:20:45.420 --> 00:20:46.720
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:48.020
&gt;&gt; Because he was in
the original movie.

00:20:48.020 --> 00:20:49.320
&gt;&gt; Yes, yes.

00:20:49.320 --> 00:20:51.360
&gt;&gt; So what does that do to
you as a writer when you -- ?

00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:55.060
&gt;&gt; Well, it was interesting, Lynn,
because we got the terrible news

00:20:55.060 --> 00:20:58.980 position:56%
about Philip's death, I was probably
250, 300 pages into the book.

00:20:58.980 --> 00:21:00.280
&gt;&gt; Oh.

00:21:00.280 --> 00:21:03.680
&gt;&gt; And, of course, that's who I'd
been thinking about, and while,

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:10.470
as a writer, as a novelist, I
know better than to cast a novel

00:21:10.470 --> 00:21:16.460
when I'm writing it, because even
if the actor that I'm thinking

00:21:16.460 --> 00:21:21.670
about wanted to play the role, the
odds against it are still enormous,

00:21:21.670 --> 00:21:24.840
because actors of that
caliber, you know, they do two

00:21:24.840 --> 00:21:28.920
or three movies a year
sometimes, and the chances

00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:32.030
that Philip Seymour
Hoffman would be available

00:21:32.030 --> 00:21:37.980
and would have the interest
in playing Raymer in a movie,

00:21:37.980 --> 00:21:40.660
those are pretty long odds.

00:21:40.660 --> 00:21:44.850
But he was not only -- he not only
played Raymer, but then he went

00:21:44.850 --> 00:21:52.050
on after that, of course to play
a major role in "Empire Falls."

00:21:52.050 --> 00:21:58.060
It was just impossible
not to see him.

00:21:58.060 --> 00:22:00.990
And it was also impossible not
to, you know, keep it in the back

00:22:00.990 --> 00:22:03.930
of your mind as far as
you can, but what if?

00:22:03.930 --> 00:22:07.340
What if he were able
to play this role?

00:22:07.340 --> 00:22:08.640
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:22:08.640 --> 00:22:10.680
&gt;&gt; Because seeing him
the way I was seeing him,

00:22:10.680 --> 00:22:15.130
I was also imagining something of
not only my character's inner life,

00:22:15.130 --> 00:22:19.350
but just how wonderful Philip
Seymour Hoffman always was

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:24.860
in his career, in playing
people who had kind

00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:28.360
of almost paralytic self-doubt.

00:22:28.360 --> 00:22:31.920
I mean, think of the
great roles that he had.

00:22:31.920 --> 00:22:35.570
And so many of them were about
people who were in a state

00:22:35.570 --> 00:22:42.290
of almost paralysis as a result
of insecurity, fear, self-doubt.

00:22:42.290 --> 00:22:45.780
And so I was -- I mean,
there he was.

00:22:45.780 --> 00:22:50.700
And then we got the news of
his death, and I thought,

00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:52.000
all right, now what do you do?

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:57.420
It wasn't that -- it wasn't the
obvious that, you know, I mean,

00:22:57.420 --> 00:23:02.430
now there's no chance, obviously,
the man is dead, he's not going

00:23:02.430 --> 00:23:04.040
to play Raymer in the movie.

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:06.600
It didn't have anything to
do with anything like that.

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:10.200
It was, I thought, now what do
I do with what's in my head?

00:23:10.200 --> 00:23:16.440
What do I do with the fact
that I'm seeing this man?

00:23:16.440 --> 00:23:18.940
What should I do?

00:23:18.940 --> 00:23:22.510
Should I start now thinking
in terms of somebody else?

00:23:22.510 --> 00:23:26.300
And for a while I tried to,
and it was just impossible.

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:29.460
And so I thought, you know what?

00:23:29.460 --> 00:23:30.880
Let him be the muse.

00:23:30.880 --> 00:23:32.180
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:23:32.180 --> 00:23:37.140
&gt;&gt; Because with these characters,
when I think back on all

00:23:37.140 --> 00:23:42.150
of my fictional characters, not one
single actor has ever been chosen

00:23:42.150 --> 00:23:45.880
that I would've chosen had
I been in charge of casting.

00:23:45.880 --> 00:23:51.090
Ed Harris in "Empire Falls."

00:23:51.090 --> 00:23:54.980
What a wonderful job that he did.

00:23:54.980 --> 00:24:01.770
But I had described, what I had
described, the man I had described

00:24:01.770 --> 00:24:05.610
in "Empire Falls," my
novel of "Empire Falls,"

00:24:05.610 --> 00:24:11.820
a man who had been literally eating
his mistakes for most of his life.

00:24:11.820 --> 00:24:14.080
Whenever he makes a
mistake at the grill,

00:24:14.080 --> 00:24:17.780
there's nothing left
to do but eat it.

00:24:17.780 --> 00:24:22.990
You know? And the man that
I had described, you know,

00:24:22.990 --> 00:24:25.810 position:56%
if you had been casting on my
physical descriptions would've been,

00:24:25.810 --> 00:24:28.280
I don't know, James
Gandolfini, somebody like that.

00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:29.620
A big guy.

00:24:29.620 --> 00:24:31.610
Throughout the book he's
referred to as Big Boy.

00:24:31.610 --> 00:24:32.910
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:24:32.910 --> 00:24:38.020
&gt;&gt; But the first -- and
then they cast Ed Harris.

00:24:38.020 --> 00:24:42.550
Trim, little, buff Ed Harris.

00:24:42.550 --> 00:24:45.530
And I thought what in the
world are they thinking?

00:24:45.530 --> 00:24:49.020
Are they going to make
him wear a fat suit?

00:24:49.020 --> 00:24:51.890
I just couldn't get it.

00:24:51.890 --> 00:24:53.940
I couldn't see it.

00:24:53.940 --> 00:24:55.240
And then we went on the set.

00:24:55.240 --> 00:24:58.320
My daughters and my wife and I
went on the set and we saw a daily,

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:06.440
and one of the dailies was a
shot -- was a scene with him --

00:25:06.440 --> 00:25:09.860
it took place in the diner,
and it was a scene with him

00:25:09.860 --> 00:25:12.980
and his beautiful daughter.

00:25:12.980 --> 00:25:19.220
And the way he looked at her,
I thought, there's Miles.

00:25:19.220 --> 00:25:20.520
There's Miles.

00:25:20.520 --> 00:25:26.470
And so when you write to a
particular kind of actor,

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:31.180
what you're seeing is something
physical, but what they're going

00:25:31.180 --> 00:25:33.960 position:56%
to bring to the role, if it's a
great actor, is not physical at all.

00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:38.800
And so, at some point, that
wisdom dawned on me, I guess,

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:40.410
that it was just perfectly fine

00:25:40.410 --> 00:25:44.480
to see Philip Seymour
Hoffman in my mind.

00:25:44.480 --> 00:25:49.140
Because some great actor is
going to come and find something

00:25:49.140 --> 00:25:54.040
in that character, and if
he doesn't look like the guy

00:25:54.040 --> 00:25:55.980
in my head, it doesn't matter.

00:25:55.980 --> 00:25:57.280
&gt;&gt; All right.

00:25:57.280 --> 00:25:58.580
I've got one more question
for you before we open it

00:25:58.580 --> 00:26:00.420
up for questions from the audience.

00:26:00.420 --> 00:26:02.650
Because this is something
I had talked

00:26:02.650 --> 00:26:03.950
about with you one other time.

00:26:03.950 --> 00:26:05.510
I met you this May, in May.

00:26:05.510 --> 00:26:09.030
I was thinking, as I was
reading your books recently

00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:13.510
that they span several decades,
and yet over those several decades,

00:26:13.510 --> 00:26:16.840
in each of these towns, they've
already gone through a period

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:21.190 position:56%
where the industry has left, they're
bereft, people are leaving the town

00:26:21.190 --> 00:26:22.750
because there's no jobs there.

00:26:22.750 --> 00:26:24.050
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:26:24.050 --> 00:26:25.350
&gt;&gt; People are scrounging
for a living.

00:26:25.350 --> 00:26:28.800
And yet here we are in
this election cycle, 2016,

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:30.980
and the issue of jobs
leaving the country,

00:26:30.980 --> 00:26:33.170
